@node Account configuration
@section Account configuration

@vindex gdocs-accounts
The user option @code{gdocs-accounts} is an alist of named Google accounts
with their OAuth credentials.  Each entry takes the form
@code{(NAME . ((client-id . "ID") (client-secret . "SECRET")))} where NAME
is a string identifying the account (e.g., @samp{"personal"} or @samp{"work"}),
and @code{client-id} and @code{client-secret} are OAuth 2.0 credentials that you
obtain from the Google Cloud Console (@ref{Obtaining credentials}).

When @code{gdocs-accounts} is @code{nil} or has only one entry, commands that
require an account use it automatically without prompting.  When
multiple accounts are configured, commands prompt with
@code{completing-read} to select one.  You would configure multiple accounts
when you need to access Google Docs from different Google Workspace
organizations (for example, a personal account and a work account with
separate OAuth credentials).

The default value is @code{nil}.  You must configure at least one account
before using any @samp{gdocs} commands.

@menu
* Obtaining credentials::
@end menu

@node Obtaining credentials
@subsection Obtaining credentials

To use @samp{gdocs}, you need an OAuth 2.0 @emph{client ID} and @emph{client secret}
from the Google Cloud Console.  These credentials identify your
application to Google's servers and allow it to request access to your
Google Docs and Drive data on your behalf.  They are not passwords ---
they do not grant access by themselves.  The actual authorization
happens when you run @code{gdocs-authenticate} and grant consent in your
browser.

Follow these steps to create your credentials:

@enumerate
@item
Go to the @uref{https://console.cloud.google.com/, Google Cloud Console} and sign in with the Google account
you want to use with @samp{gdocs}.

@item
Create a new project (or select an existing one):
@itemize
@item
Click the project dropdown at the top of the page.
@item
Click @strong{New Project}.
@item
Enter a name (e.g., ``Emacs gdocs'') and click @strong{Create}.
@end itemize

@item
Enable the required APIs.  Go to @strong{APIs & Services > Library} and
enable both of these:
@itemize
@item
@strong{Google Docs API} (search for ``Google Docs API'').
@item
@strong{Google Drive API} (search for ``Google Drive API'').
@end itemize

@item
Configure the OAuth consent screen.  Go to @strong{APIs & Services > OAuth
consent screen}:
@itemize
@item
Select @strong{External} as the user type (unless you have a Google
Workspace organization and want to restrict access to internal
users).
@item
Fill in the required fields: app name (e.g., ``Emacs gdocs'') and
your email address for the support and developer contact fields.
@item
On the @strong{Scopes} page, add these two scopes:
@itemize
@item
@samp{https://www.googleapis.com/auth/documents}
@item
@samp{https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive}
@end itemize
@item
On the @strong{Test users} page, add your own email address.  While the
app is in ``Testing'' status (the default), only listed test users
can authorize it.
@item
Click @strong{Save and Continue} through the remaining pages.
@end itemize

@item
Create the OAuth credentials.  Go to @strong{APIs & Services >
Credentials}:
@itemize
@item
Click @strong{Create Credentials > OAuth client ID}.
@item
Select @strong{Desktop app} as the application type.
@item
Enter a name (e.g., ``Emacs gdocs'') and click @strong{Create}.
@item
Google will display your @strong{Client ID} and @strong{Client secret}.  Copy
both values.
@end itemize

@item
Configure @samp{gdocs} with the credentials you just obtained:

@lisp
(setopt gdocs-accounts
        '(("personal" . ((client-id . "123456789-abcdef.apps.googleusercontent.com")
                         (client-secret . "GOCSPX-abcdefghijklmnop")))))
@end lisp

Replace the example values with your actual client ID and client
secret.  The name @samp{"personal"} is arbitrary; use whatever label
makes sense to you.

@item
Run @samp{M-x gdocs-authenticate}.  Your browser will open to a Google
consent screen.  Grant access, and @samp{gdocs} will store the resulting
tokens securely in @code{gdocs-token-directory}
(@ref{Account configuration}).
@end enumerate

Note: while the app remains in ``Testing'' status, Google will show a
warning screen during authorization (``Google hasn't verified this
app'').  Click @strong{Continue} to proceed.  You do not need to publish the
app for personal use --- ``Testing'' status works indefinitely for the
test users you listed in step 4.

@vindex gdocs-token-directory
The user option @code{gdocs-token-directory} specifies the directory where
OAuth token files are stored.  Each account's tokens are saved as a
JSON file named @samp{ACCOUNT-NAME.json} with restrictive file permissions
(600) to protect the sensitive token data.  Parent directories are
created automatically when needed.

The default value is the @samp{gdocs/tokens/} subdirectory of
@code{user-emacs-directory}.  You would change this if you want to store
tokens in a location managed by a secrets tool or a different
directory structure.

@node Sync behavior
@section Sync behavior

@vindex gdocs-auto-push-on-save
The user option @code{gdocs-auto-push-on-save} controls whether changes are
automatically pushed to Google Docs whenever you save a linked org
buffer.  When non-nil, saving the buffer triggers an asynchronous push
of any changes detected since the last sync.

The default value is @code{t}.  Set this to @code{nil} if you prefer to push
changes manually with @code{gdocs-push} (@ref{Pushing and pulling}).  Automatic
pushing is suppressed when the buffer is in a conflict or error state,
regardless of this setting.

@vindex gdocs-auto-pull-on-open
The user option @code{gdocs-auto-pull-on-open} controls whether a linked org
buffer automatically pulls the latest remote content when opened.  When
non-nil, opening a file that has @code{gdocs-mode} active triggers an
immediate pull to ensure you start editing the most recent version.

The default value is @code{nil}.  Enable this if you frequently collaborate
on documents and want to always start with the latest remote state.
When disabled, the buffer shows whatever was last saved locally, and you
must run @code{gdocs-pull} manually to fetch updates.

@vindex gdocs-preserve-comments
The user option @code{gdocs-preserve-comments} controls whether the push
flow checks for Google Docs comments before applying changes.  When
non-nil, the push fetches all comments via the Drive Comments API and
identifies destructive operations---element deletions and cross-type
modifications---that would destroy anchored comments.  For each at-risk
operation, you are prompted with @code{y-or-n-p} showing the comment author
and content.  Declined deletions are removed from the request batch, so
the commented elements remain in the remote document.

The default value is @code{t}.  Set this to @code{nil} if you never use Google
Docs comments and want to skip the extra API call on each push.  This
option works with both manual pushes and auto-push-on-save
(@ref{Comment-aware push}).

@node File storage
@section File storage

@vindex gdocs-directory
The user option @code{gdocs-directory} specifies the default directory where
newly imported org files are saved.  When you use @code{gdocs-open} to fetch
a Google Doc for the first time, the resulting org file is written to
this directory with a filename derived from the document title.

The default value is @samp{~/org/gdocs/}.  The directory is created
automatically if it does not exist.  If you already have an org file
and use @code{gdocs-create} or @code{gdocs-link}, the file stays at its current
location regardless of this setting.

@node Org tagging
@section Org tagging

@vindex gdocs-org-tag
The user option @code{gdocs-org-tag} specifies an org tag to add to the
first heading of linked org files.  When non-nil, every org file that
has a Google Doc counterpart receives this tag on its first heading,
making it easy to filter linked files in agenda views or tag-based
searches.

The value is a string (e.g., @samp{"gdocs"}) or @code{nil} to disable tagging.
The default value is @samp{"gdocs"}.  The tag is added automatically when
you link, open, or create a document, and removed when you unlink
(@ref{Linking and unlinking}).

@node Cross-document link resolution
@section Cross-document link resolution

@vindex gdocs-link-directories
The user option @code{gdocs-link-directories} specifies additional
directories to scan when resolving cross-document links during
push.  When you push an org file that contains @samp{file:} or @samp{id:} links
pointing to other org files with Google Doc counterparts, the
converter replaces those links with Google Docs URLs so they work in
the browser.  @code{gdocs-directory} (@ref{File storage}) is always scanned;
this option lets you add further directories that also contain linked
org files.

The value is a list of directory paths.  The default value is @code{nil},
meaning only @code{gdocs-directory} is scanned.  You would add directories
here if your linked org files are spread across multiple locations
(for example, a project-specific directory alongside your main gdocs
directory).

