@node Authentication (2)
@section Authentication

@findex gdocs-auth-select-account
@findex gdocs-auth-get-access-token
The function @code{gdocs-auth-select-account} selects a Google account from
@code{gdocs-accounts}.  If only one account is configured, it returns that
account's name without prompting.  If multiple accounts exist, it
prompts via @code{completing-read} with an optional PROMPT argument.  It
signals an error if @code{gdocs-accounts} is @code{nil}.  This function is used
internally by most commands but is also available for use in custom
workflows or hooks.

The function @code{gdocs-auth-get-access-token} ensures a valid OAuth access
token for a given account, then calls a callback with the token string.
If the token is expired or about to expire (within a 60-second safety
margin), it refreshes the token asynchronously before calling the
callback.  If no token exists, it initiates the full OAuth flow.  This
function is the primary entry point for all API operations that need
authentication.

@node API client (1)
@section API client

@menu
* Google Docs API::
* Google Drive API::
@end menu

@node Google Docs API
@subsection Google Docs API

@findex gdocs-api-get-document
@findex gdocs-api-batch-update
@findex gdocs-api-create-document
The function @code{gdocs-api-get-document} fetches a Google Docs document by
its ID@.  It calls CALLBACK with the parsed JSON document structure.
This is used internally by @code{gdocs-pull} to retrieve the remote document
state.

The function @code{gdocs-api-batch-update} sends a list of @code{batchUpdate}
requests to a document, which is how all modifications (insertions,
deletions, style changes) are applied to Google Docs.  The REQUESTS
argument is a list of request alists as specified by the Google Docs
API@.  This function is called by both the incremental diff engine and
full replacement paths.

The function @code{gdocs-api-create-document} creates a new empty Google
Docs document with a given title.  The callback receives the response
JSON, which includes the new @samp{documentId}.

All three functions accept an optional ACCOUNT argument; when @code{nil},
the default account is selected automatically
(@ref{Account configuration}).

@node Google Drive API
@subsection Google Drive API

@findex gdocs-api-get-file-metadata
@findex gdocs-api-list-files
@findex gdocs-api-upload-image
@findex gdocs-api-search-files
The function @code{gdocs-api-get-file-metadata} fetches metadata for a
Google Drive file, including its @samp{id}, @samp{name}, @samp{modifiedTime},
@samp{version}, and @samp{headRevisionId}.  The revision ID is used by the pull
mechanism to detect whether the remote document has changed
(@ref{Pushing and pulling}).

The function @code{gdocs-api-list-files} lists Google Drive files matching a
query string (using Drive's query syntax).  It supports pagination via
an optional PAGE-TOKEN argument.

The function @code{gdocs-api-upload-image} uploads a local image file to
Google Drive using a multipart upload.  It determines the MIME type
from the file extension (PNG, JPEG, GIF, WebP, and SVG are supported).
An optional FOLDER-ID argument specifies the parent folder in Drive.

The function @code{gdocs-api-search-files} performs a full-text search across
Google Drive by wrapping @code{gdocs-api-list-files} with a
@samp{fullText contains} query.

@findex gdocs-api-list-comments
The function @code{gdocs-api-list-comments} fetches all comments on a Google
Drive file via the Drive Comments API@.  It paginates automatically with
a page size of 100, collecting results across pages before calling
CALLBACK with the complete list of comment alists.  Each comment
includes its @samp{id}, @samp{content}, @samp{quotedFileContent} (the anchored text),
@samp{author}, @samp{createdTime}, @samp{resolved} state, and nested @samp{replies}.  This
function is used by the comment-aware push flow when
@code{gdocs-preserve-comments} is non-nil (@ref{Comment-aware push}).

@findex gdocs-api-resolve-comment
The function @code{gdocs-api-resolve-comment} resolves a comment on a Google
Drive file via the Drive Comments API@.  It takes a FILE-ID and
COMMENT-ID and marks the comment as resolved by sending a PATCH request
that sets the @samp{resolved} field to true.  CALLBACK receives the updated
comment alist.  This function is used by the comment-aware push flow
when the user chooses the ``resolve & delete'' action
(@ref{Comment-aware push}).

@findex gdocs-api-rename-file
@findex gdocs-api-create-folder
@findex gdocs-api-move-file
The function @code{gdocs-api-rename-file} renames a Google Drive file
identified by FILE-ID to NEW-NAME@.  This is used internally by
@code{gdocs-push} when the local @samp{#+TITLE} has changed since the last sync,
so the Google Doc title stays in sync with the org file
(@ref{Pushing and pulling}).

The function @code{gdocs-api-create-folder} creates a new folder in Google
Drive.  An optional PARENT-FOLDER-ID argument places the folder inside
a specific parent.  This function is called by @code{gdocs-create-folder}
when building the Drive folder hierarchy for local directories
(@ref{Directory linking}).

The function @code{gdocs-api-move-file} moves a Google Drive file into a
different folder by adding the file to the target folder and removing
it from its current parent.  This is used by @code{gdocs-create} to place
newly created documents in the linked Drive folder
(@ref{Directory linking}).

@node Format conversion (1)
@section Format conversion

@findex gdocs-convert-org-buffer-to-ir
@findex gdocs-convert-org-string-to-ir
@findex gdocs-convert-org-buffer-to-segments
@findex gdocs-convert-ir-to-org
@findex gdocs-convert-docs-json-to-ir
@findex gdocs-convert-ir-to-docs-requests
All conversion passes through a flat list of intermediate
representation (IR) element plists, which serves as the canonical
interchange format shared with the diff engine (@ref{Diff engine}).

The function @code{gdocs-convert-org-buffer-to-ir} parses the current org
buffer using @code{org-element-parse-buffer} and returns an IR element list.
The related function @code{gdocs-convert-org-string-to-ir} does the same but
accepts an org-mode string rather than operating on the current buffer.

The function @code{gdocs-convert-org-buffer-to-segments} is a variant of
@code{gdocs-convert-org-buffer-to-ir} designed for the three-way merge.
Instead of returning a flat IR list, it returns a plist with four keys:
@code{:ir} (the full IR element list), @code{:segments} (a list of segment plists,
each pairing an @code{:ir-element} with its @code{:org-text} region), @code{:preamble}
(buffer text before the first body element, including the property
drawer and @samp{#+TITLE:} line), and @code{:postamble} (text after the last
element).  By preserving the mapping between IR
elements and their original org text, the three-way merge can retain
org-only metadata (property drawers, TODO keywords, tags) that would
otherwise be lost during conversion (@ref{Sync engine}).

The function @code{gdocs-convert-ir-to-org} converts an IR element list back
to a well-formatted org-mode string.  This is the inverse of
@code{gdocs-convert-org-buffer-to-ir} and is used when pulling remote
changes.

The function @code{gdocs-convert-docs-json-to-ir} converts a Google Docs API
JSON response (an alist with keys like @samp{body}, @samp{title}, @samp{lists}, and
@samp{namedRanges}) to an IR element list.  It walks the document structure
and maps each structural element to its IR equivalent.  Each resulting
IR element carries @samp{:doc-start} and @samp{:doc-end} properties copied from
the JSON's @code{startIndex} and @code{endIndex}, giving the diff engine
authoritative UTF-16 document positions
(@ref{Intermediate representation}).

The function @code{gdocs-convert-ir-to-docs-requests} converts an IR element
list to a list of Google Docs @code{batchUpdate} request alists.  It tracks
a running UTF-16 insertion index starting at 1 (the beginning of the
Google Docs body).  This function is used for full document replacement
and by the diff engine for incremental insertions.

@node Diff engine (1)
@section Diff engine

@findex gdocs-diff-generate
@findex gdocs-diff-compute-operations
@findex gdocs-diff-generate-from-ops
The function @code{gdocs-diff-generate} is the main entry point of the diff
engine.  It compares two IR element lists (OLD-IR and NEW-IR) and
returns a list of @code{batchUpdate} request plists representing the minimal
changes needed.  Internally, it computes content-based keys for each
element, runs a longest-common-subsequence (LCS) algorithm to identify
kept, deleted, inserted, and modified elements, and generates the
appropriate API requests.

An optional START-INDEX argument specifies the UTF-16 code unit offset
where the first IR element begins in the document body (default 1).
The sync engine uses this to account for title elements that precede the
diffable body content (@ref{Sync engine}).  When the old IR carries
@samp{:doc-start} / @samp{:doc-end} properties (as produced by
@code{gdocs-convert-docs-json-to-ir}), the engine uses those authoritative
positions; otherwise it computes positions from element text lengths.
Requests are ordered for correct index stability: deletions and
modifications processed from highest index to lowest, with insertions
interleaved so that earlier operations do not shift indices of later
ones.

For workflows that need to inspect or filter diff operations before
generating API requests, two lower-level functions are available.  The
function @code{gdocs-diff-compute-operations} returns the raw diff operation
list (with @code{:op} values of @code{keep}, @code{delete}, @code{insert}, or @code{modify})
without generating requests.  The function
@code{gdocs-diff-generate-from-ops} accepts a pre-computed operation list and
produces the corresponding API requests.  The comment-aware push flow
uses this two-step API to filter declined deletions before generating
the final request batch (@ref{Comment-aware push}).

@node Conflict resolution (2)
@section Conflict resolution

@findex gdocs-merge-start
The function @code{gdocs-merge-start} opens the conflict resolution
interface.  It takes two org-mode strings (local and remote) and a
callback function.  It computes hunks by running an LCS diff on the
line-level differences, sets up the @samp{*gdocs-merge*} buffer with
color-coded overlays for conflicts, and displays it.  When the user
finalizes the merge, the callback is called with the resulting merged
org string.

This function is called internally by the sync engine when a pull
detects both local and remote changes (@ref{Conflict resolution}).

@node Authentication (1)
@chapter Authentication

@menu
* OAuth flow::
* Token management::
* Multi-account support::
@end menu

@node OAuth flow
@section OAuth flow

The OAuth 2.0 flow works as follows:

@enumerate
@item
The user runs @samp{M-x gdocs-authenticate}.
@item
A temporary local HTTP server starts on a random high port to
receive the authorization callback.
@item
The user's default browser opens to Google's OAuth consent screen.
@item
After the user grants consent, Google redirects to the local server
with an authorization code.
@item
The package exchanges the code for access and refresh tokens.
@item
Tokens are stored in @code{gdocs-token-directory} with 600 permissions.
@end enumerate

The package requests two OAuth scopes:

@itemize
@item
@samp{https://www.googleapis.com/auth/documents} for reading and writing
Google Docs.
@item
@samp{https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive} for listing, browsing, and
creating files in Google Drive.
@end itemize

@node Token management
@section Token management

Access tokens are refreshed automatically before each API call when
they are expired or within 60 seconds of expiry.  The refresh uses the
stored refresh token and happens asynchronously, so Emacs is never
blocked.  Each token file also stores the @samp{client_id} and
@samp{client_secret} so that token refreshes work without re-reading
@code{gdocs-accounts}.

If no token file exists for an account (e.g., after running
@code{gdocs-logout}), the next API operation triggers a fresh OAuth flow.

@node Multi-account support
@section Multi-account support

Each entry in @code{gdocs-accounts} is an independent account with its own
OAuth credentials and token file.  Linked org files remember which
account they are associated with via the @samp{GDOCS_ACCOUNT} property in
the file-level property drawer (@ref{Metadata storage}).  When you open a
linked file, the stored account is used automatically.

You would configure custom OAuth credentials per account if you want to
avoid shared rate limits or if your organization requires its own OAuth
application.

@node API client
@chapter API client

@menu
* Error handling and retries::
* Progress indication::
@end menu

@node Error handling and retries
@section Error handling and retries

All API requests include automatic retry logic for transient errors.
When the server returns HTTP 429 (rate limited), 500 (internal server
error), or 503 (service unavailable), the request is retried with
exponential backoff up to three times.  If the response includes a
@samp{Retry-After} header, its value is used as the delay; otherwise, the
delay follows the pattern 1s, 2s, 4s, capped at 30 seconds.

Authentication failures (HTTP 401 or 403) produce a clear error message
directing you to run @code{gdocs-authenticate} to re-authorize.

@node Progress indication
@section Progress indication

While API requests are in flight, the global modeline displays
@samp{[GDocs: syncing...]} to indicate that a network operation is in
progress.  The indicator disappears when all pending requests complete.

@node Format conversion
@chapter Format conversion

@menu
* Supported element mapping::
* Intermediate representation::
* Org-only constructs::
* Google Docs-only constructs::
@end menu

@node Supported element mapping
@section Supported element mapping

The converter handles the following bidirectional mapping between
org-mode elements and Google Docs constructs:

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Org element
@tab Google Docs equivalent
@item @samp{#+TITLE:}
@tab Title paragraph style
@item @samp{* Heading} (level 1--6)
@tab Heading 1--6 paragraph style
@item @samp{* Heading} (level 7+)
@tab Heading 6 (flattened)
@item Body text / paragraphs
@tab Normal text paragraphs
@item @samp{*bold*}
@tab Bold text run
@item @samp{/italic/}
@tab Italic text run
@item @samp{_underline_}
@tab Underline text run
@item @samp{+strikethrough+}
@tab Strikethrough text run
@item @code{=verbatim=} / @samp{~code~}
@tab Monospace font text run
@item @samp{[[url][description]]}
@tab Hyperlink
@item Unordered lists (@samp{-}, @samp{+})
@tab Bullet list
@item Ordered lists (@samp{1.}, @samp{1)})
@tab Numbered list
@item Nested lists
@tab Nested list with nesting level
@item Checkbox items (@samp{[ ]}, @samp{[X]})
@tab Checklist items
@item Tables
@tab Google Docs table
@item Horizontal rules (@samp{-----})
@tab Horizontal rule (section break)
@item Block quotes
@tab Indented paragraph or custom style
@item Footnotes (@samp{[fn:1]})
@tab Google Docs footnote
@item Images (@samp{[[file:img.png]]})
@tab Inline image (uploaded to Drive)
@end multitable

@vindex gdocs-convert-monospace-font-families
Google Docs has no native ``code'' text style, so the converter uses a
font-based heuristic: when pulling, any text run whose font family
appears in the variable @code{gdocs-convert-monospace-font-families} is
treated as code (mapped to @samp{~code~} in org-mode).  When pushing, code
runs are set to the first font in the list (@samp{Courier New} by default).
The recognized families are @samp{Courier New}, @samp{Consolas}, @samp{Source Code
Pro}, @samp{Roboto Mono}, and @samp{Courier}.  You can customize this list if
your documents use a different monospace font.

@node Intermediate representation
@section Intermediate representation

All conversion passes through a flat list of IR element plists rather
than directly translating between org-mode and Google Docs JSON@.  Each
IR element has a @samp{:type} (e.g., @code{paragraph}, @code{table},
@code{horizontal-rule}), a @samp{:style} (e.g., @code{normal}, @code{heading-1}), and
@samp{:contents} (a list of text runs with formatting properties like
@samp{:bold}, @samp{:italic}, @samp{:link}, etc.).

When the IR is produced from Google Docs JSON (via
@code{gdocs-convert-docs-json-to-ir}), each element also carries
@samp{:doc-start} and @samp{:doc-end} properties recording the element's
@code{startIndex} and @code{endIndex} from the JSON@.  These authoritative UTF-16
byte offsets allow the diff engine to use the exact document positions
reported by the API rather than re-computing them from text lengths
(@ref{Diff engine}).

This architecture means the diff engine only needs to understand the IR
format, not both org-mode and Google Docs JSON independently.

@node Org-only constructs
@section Org-only constructs

Certain org-mode constructs have no direct Google Docs equivalent.
These are preserved as special markers in the Google Doc so they survive
round-trips:

@itemize
@item
@strong{TODO keywords}: rendered as styled text with a preservation comment.
@item
@strong{Tags}: same treatment as TODO keywords.
@item
@strong{Timestamps} (@samp{SCHEDULED:}, @samp{DEADLINE:}, active/inactive): preserved
as markers.
@item
@strong{Properties and drawers}: preserved as markers, not rendered visually.
@item
@strong{Source code blocks}: rendered as monospace-formatted text with the
full org syntax in a comment.
@item
@strong{@LaTeX{} fragments}: rendered as monospace text with the raw @LaTeX{} in a
comment.
@item
@strong{Org keywords} (@samp{#+AUTHOR:}, @samp{#+DATE:}, etc.): preserved as markers
at the top of the document.
@item
@strong{Custom IDs and anchors}: preserved as comments.
@end itemize

@node Google Docs-only constructs
@section Google Docs-only constructs

Similarly, some Google Docs constructs have no org equivalent and are
preserved as opaque org markers:

@itemize
@item
Page breaks: @samp{#+GDOCS_PAGE_BREAK:}
@item
Headers/footers: @samp{#+GDOCS_HEADER:} / @samp{#+GDOCS_FOOTER:}
@item
Page numbers: @samp{#+GDOCS_PAGE_NUMBER:}
@item
Table of contents: @samp{#+GDOCS_TOC:}
@item
Embedded drawings: @samp{#+GDOCS_DRAWING:}
@item
Charts: @samp{#+GDOCS_CHART:}
@item
Named styles / custom formatting: preserved as inline markers
@end itemize

@node Sync engine
@chapter Sync engine

@menu
* Metadata storage::
* Shadow copy::
* Push serialization::
* Post-push list nesting fixup::
@end menu

@node Metadata storage
@section Metadata storage

Each linked org file stores sync metadata in a file-level property
drawer at the top of the file:

@example
:PROPERTIES:
:GDOCS_DOCUMENT_ID: 1BxiMVs0XRA5nFMdKvBdBZjgmUUqptlbs74OgVE2upms
:GDOCS_ACCOUNT: personal
:GDOCS_REVISION_ID: ALm37BVT...
:GDOCS_LAST_SYNC: 2024-01-15T10:30:00+0000
:END:
@end example

The property drawer is the standard org-mode mechanism for
document-level metadata.  All four properties are persisted to the
file, so revision tracking and last-sync timestamps survive across
Emacs sessions.  The drawer is read via @code{org-entry-get} and written
via @code{org-entry-put}, using standard org APIs rather than the Emacs
file-local variable machinery.

Directories linked to Google Drive folders (@ref{Directory linking}) store
their association in @samp{.dir-locals.el} rather than per-file:

@example
((org-mode . ((gdocs-folder-id . "1A2B3C4D5E6F...")
              (gdocs-account . "personal"))))
@end example

This means every org file in the directory inherits the folder and
account settings.  @code{gdocs-create} uses these values to place new
documents in the correct Drive folder.

@node Shadow copy
@section Shadow copy

The sync engine maintains a buffer-local @emph{shadow IR}: the intermediate
representation of the last-synced state.  This shadow enables
incremental diffs on push and conflict detection on pull.

On the first open of a linked file after an Emacs restart, the shadow
is @code{nil}.  The next push fetches the remote document and diffs against
it (rather than against the missing shadow), so incremental diffing
still works and comment anchors are preserved.  If
@code{gdocs-auto-pull-on-open} is non-nil, the pull establishes the shadow
baseline automatically so that subsequent pushes diff against the
known-good shadow.

@node Push serialization
@section Push serialization

Pushes are serialized to prevent race conditions.  If a push is already
in flight when another is triggered (e.g., by a rapid save), the second
push is queued and executes automatically when the first completes.
This ensures that the shadow copy is always consistent with what was
last sent to the API@.

@node Post-push list nesting fixup
@section Post-push list nesting fixup

The diff engine emits @code{createParagraphBullets} requests for new list
items and for modifications that change the list type or nesting level.
These per-paragraph requests always produce flat (level-0) lists.  The
full conversion path has a separate mechanism
(@code{gdocs-convert--fixup-list-nesting}) that groups bullets and inserts
leading tabs so that the API infers correct nesting levels, but the diff
path cannot use that mechanism because it interleaves modifications with
insertions at varying document positions.

When a content modification does not change the list structure (same
type and level), the diff engine suppresses the @code{createParagraphBullets}
request entirely.  The trailing newline is preserved during paragraph
modifications, which keeps the paragraph in its existing Google Docs
list object.  Re-emitting a bullet request with a fixed preset would
overwrite the alternated preset assigned during document creation and
cause Google Docs to merge separate numbered lists into one continuous
sequence.

To restore correct nesting, the sync engine runs a second
@code{batchUpdate} pass after the main push succeeds, but only when the
local IR contains nested list items (level > 0).  The fixup proceeds
as follows:

@enumerate
@item
Fetch the just-pushed document to obtain current paragraph ranges.

@item
Align local and remote IR elements by plain-text content using the
same LCS approach as the diff engine, so that each local element
(which carries the correct @samp{:level} from the org source) is paired
with its remote counterpart (which carries @samp{:doc-start} /
@samp{:doc-end} positions).

@item
Build element-range plists that merge local list info with remote
document positions.  The local element's @samp{:list} always takes
precedence, even when nil — this ensures that headings erroneously
bulleted by the API are correctly treated as non-list elements by
the guard logic in step 6.

@item
Identify contiguous list groups that contain at least one element
at level > 0.

@item
For each such group, emit four kinds of requests in order:
@itemize
@item
@code{deleteParagraphBullets} to remove the flat bullets for the
group range.
@item
@code{updateParagraphStyle} to reset @samp{indentStart} and
@samp{indentFirstLine} to zero, so only leading tabs signal nesting
depth.
@item
@code{insertText} to insert @emph{N} tab characters at each nested
paragraph's @samp{startIndex} (where @emph{N} is the nesting level).
Insertions are sorted by descending index to maintain correct
positions.
@item
A per-group @code{createParagraphBullets} request.  The API counts
the leading tabs, assigns the correct nesting levels, and
removes the tabs afterward.
@end itemize

@item
Emit defensive @code{deleteParagraphBullets} requests for non-list
paragraphs adjacent to the list groups.  The Google Docs API can
extend bullet formatting to heading paragraphs near
@code{createParagraphBullets} ranges, so these guards prevent headings
from being accidentally turned into bullet points.
@end enumerate

The fixup keeps the push lock held until completion, so any queued
push waits until nesting is fully resolved before proceeding
(@ref{Push serialization}).  If the local IR has no nested list items,
the fixup is skipped entirely and the push completes in a single
round trip.

@node Diff engine
@chapter Diff engine

The incremental diff engine computes the minimal set of Google Docs API
@code{batchUpdate} requests to transform the remote document from its
last-known state to the current org state.

@menu
* Approach::
* Word-level diff::
* Text-style reset::
* Comment-aware push::
@end menu

@node Approach
@section Approach

@enumerate
@item
Produce content-based keys for each element in the old and new IRs.
Keys capture type, style, text content, and formatting, so elements
with identical content produce identical keys.

@item
Run a longest-common-subsequence (LCS) algorithm on the key lists to
identify which elements are kept, deleted, inserted, or modified.
Adjacent delete+insert pairs of the same type are collapsed into
modify operations.

@item
Compute the UTF-16 document position of each old element.  When the
old IR was produced from Google Docs JSON, elements carry
@samp{:doc-start} / @samp{:doc-end} properties with the authoritative byte
offsets reported by the API; the engine uses those directly.  For IR
produced from org-mode (which lacks document positions), it falls
back to computing positions from element text lengths.  Insertion
points for new elements are determined by the end position of the
nearest preceding kept or modified element; modified elements are
valid anchors because they still occupy a known position in the old
document.

@item
Map operations to API requests:
@itemize
@item
@strong{Insert}: @code{InsertText}, @code{InsertTable}, @code{CreateParagraphBullets}, etc.
@item
@strong{Delete}: @code{DeleteContentRange}.
@item
@strong{Modify}: for style-only changes, @code{UpdateParagraphStyle}; for
formatting-only changes, @code{UpdateTextStyle}; for content changes,
word-level surgical diff (@ref{Word-level diff}).
@end itemize

@item
Order requests correctly: deletions in reverse index order (highest
first), then insertions in forward order.  This is necessary because
the Google Docs API processes requests sequentially and earlier
operations shift later indices.
@end enumerate

@node Word-level diff
@section Word-level diff

When a paragraph's text content changes, the diff engine performs a
word-level diff rather than deleting all text and re-inserting it.
This is critical for preserving Google Docs comments: comments are
anchored to specific text ranges via opaque internal identifiers that
cannot be recreated through any API@.  A full delete+re-insert destroys
all comment anchors, even on text that did not change.

The word-level algorithm works as follows:

@enumerate
@item
Tokenize the old and new paragraph text into alternating word tokens
(contiguous non-whitespace) and whitespace tokens (contiguous spaces
or tabs).  This preserves exact spacing.

@item
Run the LCS algorithm on the token strings to identify which tokens
are kept, deleted, or inserted.

@item
Collapse adjacent same-operation tokens into contiguous ranges.

@item
Generate @code{DeleteContentRange} requests for deleted ranges (sorted
highest to lowest by document index) and @code{InsertText} requests for
inserted text at the correct post-deletion positions.

@item
Apply paragraph style, text formatting, and list property requests
for the full new paragraph extent (same as before).
@end enumerate

Token offsets are computed in UTF-16 code units using
@code{gdocs-convert--string-to-utf16-length} to handle non-BMP characters
(such as emoji) that require surrogate pairs.  Even a fully rewritten
paragraph produces correct operations.  The word-level approach is used
whenever the list structure is unchanged (same type and level, or both
non-list); modifications that change the list type or nesting level fall
back to a bulk replacement to handle the tab prefix and bullet preset
changes that list transitions require.

@node Text-style reset
@section Text-style reset

When new text is inserted into a Google Doc---whether by the full
conversion path or by the incremental diff engine---it inherits the
formatting of adjacent text.  This means that inserting a plain
paragraph next to a bold one would produce bold text unless the
formatting is explicitly cleared.

To prevent inherited formatting from bleeding into new content, every
text insertion is followed by an @code{updateTextStyle} request that resets
all character-level formatting across the inserted range.  The reset
clears bold, italic, underline, strikethrough, @code{weightedFontFamily},
@code{baselineOffset}, @code{foregroundColor}, and @code{backgroundColor} by listing
them in the API's @code{fields} mask with only default values in the
@code{textStyle} body.  Fields present in the mask but absent from the body
are reset to their defaults by the Google Docs API@.  After the reset,
per-run style requests re-apply only the formatting that the org source
actually specifies.  This two-step approach (reset then re-apply)
ensures that every text run matches the org source exactly, regardless
of surrounding context.

@node Comment-aware push
@section Comment-aware push

When @code{gdocs-preserve-comments} is non-nil (@ref{Sync behavior}), the push
flow adds a comment protection step between computing the diff and
sending the batch update.  The extended flow is:

@enumerate
@item
Fetch the remote document (as before).
@item
Fetch all comments on the document via the Drive Comments API
(@code{gdocs-api-list-comments}).  Deleted and resolved comments are
excluded from the mapping, so they never trigger prompts.
@item
Compute the diff operations
(@code{gdocs-diff-compute-operations}).
@item
For each destructive operation (element deletion or cross-type
modification), check whether the target element has comments anchored
to it.  A comment is considered ``on'' an element if the comment's
@samp{quotedFileContent.value} appears as a substring of the element's
plain text.
@item
Prompt the user for each at-risk operation via a single-key prompt
showing the element text, comment author, and comment content.  The
prompt offers four actions:
@itemize
@item
@samp{[s]kip} -- keep the element in the remote document, preserving the
comment.
@item
@samp{[d]elete} -- proceed with the deletion, destroying the comment.
@item
@samp{[o]pen} -- open the comment in the browser using the Google Docs
comment URL (@samp{https://docs.google.com/document/d/DOC-ID/edit?disco=COMMENT-ID}),
then re-prompt for the same element so you can inspect the comment
in context before deciding.
@item
@samp{[r]esolve & delete} -- resolve the comment via the Drive Comments
API (@code{gdocs-api-resolve-comment}) before proceeding with the
deletion.  This marks the discussion as resolved while still
removing the element from the document.
@end itemize
Uppercase variants (@samp{S}, @samp{D}, @samp{R}) apply the chosen action to all
remaining conflicts, so you do not have to answer individually for
every at-risk element.
@item
Remove declined (skipped) operations from the diff operation list.
@item
Generate API requests from the filtered operations
(@code{gdocs-diff-generate-from-ops}).
@item
Send the batch update.
@item
Reconstruct the shadow IR to account for declined deletions: the
shadow starts with the local IR, and declined elements (from the
remote IR) are re-inserted at the correct positions.
@end enumerate

Declined elements remain in the remote document.  On the next push, the
diff will again classify them as deletions and prompt again.

Comments without quoted text (document-level comments) are never
considered at risk.  Resolved comments are still prompted, since they
represent valuable discussion history.

@node Conflict resolution
@chapter Conflict resolution

When a pull detects that the buffer has local modifications and the
remote revision has changed, the conflict resolution UI opens
automatically.  The @samp{*gdocs-merge*} buffer displays all hunks
(computed via a line-level LCS diff), with conflicts shown in a
@samp{<<<< LOCAL} / @samp{====/ =>>>> REMOTE} format.

Common (matching) lines are displayed without highlighting.  Conflict
hunks use color-coded overlays: @code{gdocs-merge-remote-face} for
unresolved conflicts, @code{gdocs-merge-resolved-face} for resolved ones.

After resolving all hunks and finalizing with @samp{C-c C-c}, the merged
content replaces the buffer, the shadow IR is updated, and the buffer
is saved (which triggers a push if auto-push is enabled).

@node Minor mode
@chapter Minor mode

@findex gdocs-mode
The minor mode @code{gdocs-mode} is activated on org buffers linked to a
Google Doc.  It provides:

@itemize
@item
Automatic push on save (via @code{after-save-hook}) when
@code{gdocs-auto-push-on-save} is non-nil.
@item
Modeline status display showing the sync state:
@itemize
@item
@samp{GDocs:synced} when in sync.
@item
@samp{GDocs:modified} when local changes have not been pushed.
@item
@samp{GDocs:pushing} while a push is in progress.
@item
@samp{GDocs:conflict} when remote changes conflict with local ones.
@item
@samp{GDocs:error} when the last sync failed.
@end itemize
@item
Keybindings under the @samp{C-c g} prefix (@ref{Keybindings}).
@end itemize

The mode activates automatically when you open an org file that has a
@samp{GDOCS_DOCUMENT_ID} property in its file-level property drawer (via a
hook on @code{org-mode-hook}).  If buffers were restored at startup before
gdocs loaded (e.g. by @code{desktop-save-mode}), gdocs scans already-open
org buffers at load time and activates the mode retroactively.  You
can also toggle it manually.

